SIMPLE: hierarchy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hierarchy
<hw>Hi"er*arch`y</hw> <pr>(h⟦imac⟧"⟦etil⟧r*⟦aum⟧rk`⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Hierarchies</plw>
<pr>(h⟦imac⟧"⟦etil⟧r*⟦aum⟧rk`⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>'ierarchi`a</grk>: cf. F. <ets>hi⟦eacute⟧rarchie</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Dominion or authority in sacred things.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A body of officials disposed organically in ranks
and orders each subordinate to the one above it; a body of
ecclesiastical rulers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A form of government administered in the church by
patriarchs, metropolitans, archbishops, bishops, and, in an inferior
degree, by priests.</def> <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A rank or order of holy beings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Standards and gonfalons . . . for distinction serve⟦br⟧
Of <qex>hierarchies</qex>, of orders, and degrees.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Math., Logic, Computers)</fld> <def>Any group of
objects ranked so that every one but the topmost is subordinate to a
specified one above it; also, the entire set of ordering relations
between such objects. The ordering relation between each object and the
one above is called a <it>hierarchical relation</it>.</def>
<note>Classification schemes, as in biology, usually form
<ex>hierarchies</ex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hieratic</ent>⟦br⟧
